  "prompt": "What is an optically active material? What do they do?",
  "response": "An optically active material is a substance that can rotate the plane of polarization of linearly polarized light as it passes through the material. Here are key details about optically active materials:\n\n1. Characteristics:\n- Asymmetric molecular structure\n- Chiral molecules with non-superimposable mirror images\n- Rotate plane-polarized light either clockwise or counterclockwise\n\n2. Types of optically active materials:\n- Organic compounds (sugars, amino acids)\n- Crystals\n- Some liquid solutions\n- Certain biological molecules\n\n3. What they do:\n- Change the orientation of light's polarization plane\n- Exhibit different optical properties depending on molecular structure\n- Can distinguish between left and right-handed molecular configurations\n\n4. Applications:\n- Pharmaceutical research\n- Chemistry analysis\n- Crystallography\n- Biochemistry\n- Optical communication technologies\n- Optical sensors\n\n5. Measurement:\n- Measured using polarimeters\n- Quantified by specific rotation angle\n- Depends on material composition, temperature, and light wavelength\n\nThe ability to rotate polarized light is a result of the material's molecular asymmetry and provides valuable insights into molecular structure and composition.",
